node.text:
❄️ Snow in summer?⁠
⁠
Canada's highest paved mountain pass, Highwood Pass in Kananaskis Country, is so high up that sometimes you can even see snow in the middle of summer. ⁠
⁠
📷 LP Staffer @alex.p.butler traveled to Banff this summer with her family and was delighted to find white capped mountains during the drive.⁠
⁠
🗣  In her words: "I grew up exploring the Rocky Mountains, but every time I return home I feel a renewed sense of awe at their beauty. And since I wasn’t able to get back for the holidays last year, I was pretty thrilled to see a bit of snow on my summer vacation."⁠
⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Lonely Planet in Hang Múa - Ninh Bình with @amanda_mccadams. May be an image of mountain and nature.

node.text:
😍 This is the reward you get when you wake up before sunrise and climb up 500 stairs in the heart of Ninh Binh Province, Vietnam. ⁠
⁠
📷  LP Staffer @amanda_mccadams photographed this magical spot while working a project shooting the UNESCO World Heritage Sites in Vietnam. ⁠
⁠
🗣  In her words: "I wanted to make sure I got here really early so I could be set up before sunrise. I borrowed a bike from the place I was staying and rode in the dark for several miles. When I got there I had plenty of time but I was so excited I still practically raced up the stairs. It was worth it. I was all set up before the sun came up and the view was breathtaking."⁠
⁠⁠
Let us know in the comments - would you climb 500 steps for this view? ⁠
⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Lonely Planet on September 14, 2021. May be an image of nature.

node.text:
🏆  The Grand Canyon just made it to the top of our Ultimate US travel list. 

It wasn’t easy but we ranked the top 500 travel experiences in the USA, with Grand Canyon National Park nabbing the top spot. The Grand Canyon beat out fellow national parks – Yosemite and Yellowstone, which grabbed the No. 2 and No. 3 spots, respectively. From the breathtaking views at Moran Point to the Desert view Watchtower, we’ve never heard anyone say they regretted visiting this geological wonder. 

To get to 500, we began by casting a wide net – every sight, attraction and experience across every state in the United States from Alabama to Wyoming was compiled. That list contained 46,977 entries.  🤯  From there, we tapped into our expansive network of travel writers who rated each place they’ve visited for research and then ranked them from one to five stars. Next, it was time to pull in the travel community, including Lonely Planet staff, editors and travel bloggers, to vote on their 20 favorite spots and experiences. Hundreds of votes were cast. 

After some mathematical alchemy (places that focused on sustainability and community were given extra points), we ended up with a score for each of the 500 experiences in the book.

To check out the full list, you can purchase the corresponding book, which hits bookshelves today and will make a great gift for the travel-lover on your list this holiday season, we might add! From the truly iconic to the lesser-known destinations, this list covers it all and has already sparked quite a bit of debate amongst our team.

📣 So let us know -- Which destination would be at the top of YOUR Ultimate US Travel List?

➡️ Want to see more breathtaking and inspiring US destinations in the US? Swipe on through and order your copy of the Ultimate United States Travel List.

node.text:
Hiking in Costa Rica is...well, pura vida at its finest.⁠
⁠
Earlier this summer LP staffer @sheeka.sanahori visited Costa Rica with her family. Although, on this particular day, it got a little rainy for them, she had nothing but good things to report. Be sure to read to the end for her pro tip! ⁠
⁠
⁠
🗣 "I have never felt more alive on a hike than I did on the 3.7 mile Rio Celeste trail. It started raining— no, pouring about 10 minutes into this hike. With no ponchos, we pushed ahead and committed to getting soaked.⁠
⁠
It was worth it."⁠
⁠
⭐️ Sheeka's pro tip: Make sure you get to the entrance to the Rio Celeste hike first thing in the morning. You have to have a ticket to enter. When we got there, they were closing the hike for the day, limiting only 500 hikers a day on the trail.⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Lonely Planet on September 11, 2021. May be an image of coast.

node.text:
Is there more to Mykonos than the dazzling sand and insatiable partygoers?⁠
⁠
We think so.⁠
⁠
While this Greek isle might be known for the night life there is so much more.⁠
⁠
Save this to your travel inspo folder and have fun planning your trip to this picturesque island.⁠
⁠
What to do on Mykonos⁠
⁠
🤿 Diving:⁠
 Mykonos has plenty of walls, caves and wrecks to entice beginners and advanced divers alike. Diving operators are based on Paradise Beach, Lia Beach and Kalafatis Beach. The most reputable outfits include Mykonos Diving Center and GoDive Mykonos.⁠
⁠
🏛 Historical sites: Mykonos is the gateway to the sacred island of Delos, the mythical birthplace of Apollo and Aphrodite, a Unesco World Heritage site and one of the most important and well-preserved archaeological sites in Greece. Daily boat trips depart from the pier in Hora.⁠
⁠
🚵‍♀️ Mountain biking: Mykonos island has a hilly interior, quiet backcountry roads, tranquil villages and several practically deserted beaches along the north coast. Yummy Pedals tailors guided mountain-biking tours of the island to suit your skill level.⁠
⁠
🌅 Sunset watching: Prime spots for watching the greatest free show on earth include the bars of Little Venice in Hora, Kato Mili (a classic quartet of windmills on a hillock overlooking Little Venice) and Agios Ioannis beach.⁠
⁠
🏊‍♀️ Swimming: Mykonos doesn’t lack places to take a plunge, from infinity pools at top hotels and private plunge pools to 25 beautiful sandy beaches that fringe the island.⁠
⁠
💦 Water sports: Head to the Windsurf Centre Mykonos on Kalafatis Beach for lessons, or try your hand at adrenaline-packed activities such as flyboarding, wakeboarding and wakeskating with Platys Gialos Watersports on the eponymous beach.⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Lonely Planet in New York City, N.Y.. May be an image of skyscraper and monument.

node.text:
The New York skyline is one of the most recognizable on the planet. ⁠
⁠
Rising high above the other glistening buildings of downtown Manhattan sits One World Trade Center, built on the site of the tragic terrorist attacks of September 11th, 2001. It's the tallest building in the US, standing 408 feet (124m) above the original twin towers and is part of the updated World Trade Center.⁠
⁠
With the 20th anniversary of the 2001 attacks upon us, we're thankful to have a space where so many can come to reflect and pay their respects to the lives lost and affected by that fateful day.⁠
⁠
The National September 11 Memorial & Museum, both poignant and deeply affecting, tells the story of that tragic day and its impact on, not only the US, but the entire world.  It is well worth a visit on your next trip to NYC.⁠
⁠
📷: @caitriddler

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Lonely Planet in Agawa Canyon. May be an image of train, nature and railroad.

node.text:
🍂 It's almost time to welcome fall.⁠
⁠
One of the most scenic ways to enjoy this time of year is to hop on board the Agawa Canyon Tour Train. ⁠
⁠
Tag your leaf-peeping partner and get ready.⁠
⁠
🚞 About this adventure:⁠
The ride sets off from Sault Ste Marie and covers 114 miles of unspoiled countryside.⁠
⁠
🎨 Who else loves this area:⁠
These views inspired Tom Thomson and the Group of Seven, Canada’s most prominent landscape artists, throughout the early 20th century. ⁠
⁠
🗓 When you should go:⁠
You’ll need to be quick: the leaves peak for a brief period around the end of September and beginning of October.⁠
⁠
⭐️ Want to know how to visit more beautiful places to witness the glorious fall colors all around the world? Head to the link in our bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Lonely Planet in Spain. May be an image of sky, nature and monument.

node.text:
🇪🇸 Hikers in Spain are treated to ancient ruins, historical towns, old churches and even random castles along the way. ⁠
⁠
🇪🇸 Sculpted by extensive mountain ranges surrounding a high inland plateau, Spain has nearly 6000 kilometers (3728 miles) of coastline. ⁠This means that hikers can enjoy everything from rugged cliff sides and snow capped mountains to glacial lakes and turquoise water with white sand beaches. 
⁠
📍 Albarracin,Spain 

Here is a rundown of Spain's 5 hiking routes that show off the incredibly diverse beauty of this Iberian destination.⁠
⁠
Which one do you want to do? Let us know in the comments.⁠
⁠
🥾 Peñalara⁠
Best hike for viewing glacial lakes⁠
14 km (8.7 miles), 4 hours, intermediate⁠
⁠
🥾 El Caminito del Rey ⁠
Best steep trail with archaeological highlights⁠
8 km (1.9 miles), 2.5 hours, easy⁠
⁠
🥾 La Pedriza⁠
Best hike for rugged mountains⁠
12km (7.5 miles), 3 hours, intermediate⁠
⁠
🥾 Cares Trail (Picos de Europa National Park)⁠
Best hike for dramatic scenery⁠
21.9 km, 6.5 hours, intermediate⁠
⁠
🥾 Camino de Santiago (French Way)⁠
Best historic hike to retrace pilgrims’ footsteps⁠
100 km (62 miles), 7 days, intermediate to difficult

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Lonely Planet in Khao Sok National Park. May be an image of tree and nature.

node.text:
💚 Could you use some serenity when you're finally able to take that big trip?⁠
⁠
🎍 How does the exploring the giant bamboo forest in Khao Sok National Park, Thailand sound?⁠
⁠
At the heart of this jaw-droppingly beautiful national park is the Cheow Lan Lake, an artificial reservoir created in the early 1980s by damming the nearby Klong Saeng River for an electricity project. ⁠
⁠
The vast lake measures more than 70 sq mi (180 sq km) in size, and is hemmed by towering karst and limestone outcrops along the water’s edge. ⁠
⁠
Some contend that the thick evergreen vegetation covering these hills may well count as one of the oldest rainforests in the world. ⁠
⁠
Clusters of stilted eco-huts located in remote valley gaps – outfitted with nothing but the most basic amenities – offer an unparalleled overnighting experience on the reservoir’s waters. If that’s not enough, you can go canoeing on the placid expanse of the lake, or plod along primeval forest trails in search of elephants, bears, leopards and even the smelly rafflesia flower when it blooms between October and December. ⁠
⁠
The Sok River, which trickles quietly through the gorgeous scenery, is an excellent backdrop for some laid-back river rafting. The national park is a short drive from Surat Thani, which is connected to Bangkok by a quick flight.⁠
⁠
💚 Add this to your inspo folder for when it's time for you to travel again.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Lonely Planet in Glacier National Park. May be an image of nature.

node.text:
🏔 Montana has something for everyone looking to take a walk through nature. ⁠
⁠
🥾 Naturally, many outdoor enthusiasts find themselves drawn specifically to iconic Glacier National Park, which is home to most of the best hikes in the state. ⁠
⁠
🐻 Besides being home to the largest concentration of grizzly bears on the planet, tons of moose and herds of bighorn sheep, Glacier is basically a one-stop-shop of trailheads taking hikers to magnificent destinations of varying difficulty. ⁠
⁠
📝 Put Montana on your list of hiking destinations, tap the link in our bio to explore our favorite hikes and keep these tips in mind for your next adventure.⁠
⁠
🏆 Pro tips for hiking in Montana:⁠
⁠
The intense winters of the region will limit hiking (without snowshoes) to the warmer months, roughly between April and October.⁠
⁠
The weather can change quickly, dress in layers and bring rain gear and a hat.⁠
⁠
Stay hydrated and make sure to bring plenty of water with you. Throw in some snacks packed with protein and carbs as well. ⁠
⁠
Be sure to bring a trail map, compass and flashlight (don’t depend on your cell).⁠
⁠
Montana’s wilderness is rich with wildlife, so take every precaution to avoid human-animal conflicts. Make noise on the trail to let them know you're coming and carry bear spray.

node.text:
Did you know Prague was recently named the 13th greenest city in the world?⁠
⁠
Even though you might imagine a densely packed, medieval cityscape of towers and castles, the Czech capital is actually surprisingly green. ⁠
⁠
There are plenty of places to throw down a blanket and rest your feet from the trying cobblestones. Many parks and gardens offer breathtaking views of the city, and a few even toss in the added bonus of restorative, on-site beer gardens.⁠
⁠
🍻 Who is in the mood for a sunny, green afternoon in a park in Prague? Tap the link in our bio to find all of our favorites.
